    b.
        Food is moved along the gut of the dog via a process known as peristalsis. Muscles "downstream" (further along the digestive track) of the dog contract while muscles "upstream" of the dog relax. This moves food down the gut of the dog.
    c.
        i.
            There is more protein in young dog food than adult dog food (22% vs 18%). This may reflect the fact that young dogs grow more than adult dogs, and protein is used in growth and repair.

            There is also more calcium (1% vs 0.6%) in young dog food. Again, this may reflect that young dogs are growing, and especially when getting bigger need to grow bigger bones. Calcium is crucial in bones.

            There are also more fats and phosphates in young dog food by percentage than adult dog food. The former may be so that there is more energy in the young dog food, so they have enough energy to grow. The latter may again be driven by age-related differences in nutrient need.
        ii?
            Carbohydrates such as starch are calorie-dense. This may lead to obesity in domesticated dogs, especially since they may also get fed more often.

            Carbohydrates lack proteins. In comparison to the diet of wild dogs, which consists mainly of prey animals, which are high in protein, domesticated dogs may experience deficiencies in protein, causing poor growth and development.

            It could occur that domesticated dogs produce more carbohydrase such as amylase or maltase. This would be because domesticated dogs which can absorb more nutrition from typical diets and hence better thrive may be selected for breeding.
