    b.
        When the eye focuses on a near object, light rays are diverging. This means that the lense must become more convex. To achieve this, the circular muscles contract, radial muscles relax, and the suspensory ligaments relax. This allows the light to be refracted more by the lense and hence for the eye to focus on a near object.
    c.
        i?
            A cataract affects a person's vision by causing the lens to become less transparent or translucent. This causes light to scatter as it hits those areas, causing vision to become blurred.
        ii.
            A new lense or other adjustable focusing mechanism must replace the removed lense as otherwise the person will be unable to see clearly at varying distances.
5.
    a.
        i.
            (50 - 20) / 20 * 100% = 150%
        ii.
            Scaley: 10 increases, label: breathing rate (breaths per minute)
            scalex: 2 increase, label: time since start of exercise(minutes)
        iii.
            As one exercises, one's muscles require energy. This is generated by respiring glucose, which consumes oxygen and produces carbon dioxide. Elevated levels of CO2 cause an increase in rate of breathing to expel carbon dioxide and to intake more oxygen for respiration so enough energy can be produced for exercise. Hence, we see that breathing rate in breaths per minute increases as time elapses since start of exercise.

            However, we also see that there is a plateau in breathing rate near 10-12 minutes. This may be because tidal capacity has been reached, and hence anaerobic respiration is beginning to take place, and also hence breathing rate cannot be increased.
    b.
        The breathing rate would remain high for a few minutes after the exercise has finished because:
            1. Since the breathing rate plateaued near the end, it is probably safe to assume that anaerobic respiration occurred and lactic acid was produced, placing the body in a state of oxygen debt. Hence, oxygen is consumed at an elevated level even after the exercise has finished to respire the lactic acid to bring the body out of oxygen debt.
            2. Because it takes some time for carbon dioxide levels in the bloodstream to fall, and breathing rate only reduces when CO2 levels in the bloodstream drop and sensors in the aorta and carotid artery no longer detect elevated levels of CO2.
    c.
        Advantage: does not inhibit air intake and does not affect breathing rate and performance.
        Disadvantage: you cannot measure volume of air using a shirt. Also, may be less accurate as you would have to rely on accelerometers or similar which may be confused by other movement of the torso.

6.
    a.
        One reason Drosophila are a popular choice for scientists to use in genetic studies may be because they have a short life cycle and large offspring quantities, so large quantities of mature, related (so genetically similar) individuals can be obtained rapidly as they will rapidly mature due to their short life cycle and genetically similar individuals can be obtained rapidly because they can produce lots of offspring. Also, short lifespans and lots of offspring means that many generations can be studied in a short period of time and many offspring per generation mean that random chance is less of a factor.
    b.
        i? [What has to be written in genetic diagrams?]
            Long wing, short wing: Ll
              L  l
            L Ll  Ll
            l Ll  ll

            parent genotypes: Ll, Ll
            parent phenotypes: long wings, long wings;

            offspring genotypes: Ll, Ll, Ll, ll; 75% Ll, 25% ll
            offspring phenotypes: 75% long wings : 25% short wings
            ratio of phenotypes: 3 : 1 long wings : short wings;
            ratio of genotypes: 3 : 1 Ll : ll
        ii.
            3/4 * 1/2 = 3/8
        iii.
            In total, there are 141 flies with long wings and 78 flies with short wings, and 219 flies in-total. This corresponds to 64.4% long wings and 35.6% short wings, which means there are more short winged-flies than expected.

            There are 155 male flies and 165 female flies. This is roughly in a 1:1 ratio, which is what was expected.

            Hence, there were less long-winged flies and more short-winged flies than expected. There were roughly the same amount of males and females as was expected.
    c.
        The reason why flies with short wings are not found in wild populations of Drosophila may be because flies with short wings are less maneuverable, so any naturally occurring specimen of Drosophila with short wings are more easily eaten by predators. This represents a selection pressure, which means that the allele for short wings is likely less prevalent in wild populations than in laboratory conditions.
